\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
(8 points) 
\series default
We show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sup A$
\end_inset

 does not exist.
 In fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is not bounded above.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N=\lceil x\rceil$
\end_inset

, the smallest natural number greater than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, and consider
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y=(N+1)+\frac{(-1)^{N+1}}{N+1}\in A.
\]

\end_inset

We must have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{(-1)^{N+1}}{N+1}>-1$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1)^{N+1}>-(N+1)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
